Oh   sure whatever:

Republican lawmakers in New Hampshire are seeking to make using ESG criteri=
a in state funds a crime in the latest attack on the beleaguered investing =
strategy.
Representatives led by=C2=A0Mike Belcher=C2=A0introduced=C2=A0a bill=C2=A0t=
hat would prohibit the state=E2=80=99s treasury, pension fund and executive=
 branch from using investments that consider environmental, social and gove=
rnance factors. =E2=80=9CKnowingly=E2=80=9D violating the law would be a fe=
lony punishable by not less than one year and no more than 20 years impriso=
nment, according to the proposal.

Pensions & Investments  reports:

"Executive branch agencies that are permitted to invest funds shall review =
their investments and pursue any necessary steps to ensure that no funds or=
 state-controlled investments are invested with firms that invest New Hamps=
hire funds in accounts with any regard whatsoever based on environmental, s=
ocial, and governance criteria," the bill said.
The New Hampshire Retirement System "shall adhere to their fiduciary obliga=
tion and not invest with any firm that will invest state retirement system =
funds in investment funds that consider environmental, social, and governan=
ce criteria, as the investment goal should be to obtain the highest return =
on investment for New Hampshire's taxpayers and retirees," the bill said.

Investors aren=E2=80=99t allowed to=C2=A0consider governance! Imagine if th=
is was the law; imagine if it was a felony for an investment manager to con=
sider governance =E2=80=9Cwith any regard whatsoever.=E2=80=9D
We   talked yesterday about Elon Musk=E2=80=99s plans to extort billions of=
 dollars of free stock out of Tesla Inc. by (1) owning a big chunk of Tesla=
 stock, (2)=C2=A0selling=C2=A0a lot of that stock to raise money to pursue =
his distracting personal hobbies, and then (3) telling Tesla=E2=80=99s boar=
d =E2=80=9Cwell, you know, I don=E2=80=99t own enough Tesla stock to really=
 make it worth my while to work on Tesla; if you want me to do my job as CE=
O you=E2=80=99d better double my stake to keep me motivated.=E2=80=9D Unles=
s the board gives him a ton more stock, he posted, =E2=80=9CI would prefer =
to build products outside of Tesla.=E2=80=9D
That=E2=80=99s (1) absolutely crazy corporate governance and also (2) just =
a typical Tuesday in wild Tesla corporate governance news.=C2=A0Tesla is  c=
urrently being sued over Musk=E2=80=99s=C2=A0previous enormous pay package,=
 which was supposed to motivate him to pay attention to Tesla, but which in=
 fact just gave him enough stock to sell to raise money to distract himself=
 with Twitter.
If you are a big Tesla shareholder, it might be reasonable to say something=
 like =E2=80=9Cwell, I like what Musk has done for the place, but I wish th=
e board would try to rein him in,=E2=80=9D and try to set up a meeting with=
 the Tesla board to discuss possible ways to stop giving him more stock. Or=
 it might be reasonable to say =E2=80=9Cwell, I like what Musk has done for=
 the place so far, but I=E2=80=99m increasingly worried that the governance=
 problems here are going to reduce its long-term value =E2=80=94=C2=A0what =
if Musk is telling the truth about building products outside of Tesla? =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0so I=E2=80=99m just going to sell the stock.=E2=80=9D Both of t=
hese approaches =E2=80=94=C2=A0meeting with the board to try to improve gov=
ernance to increase the long-term value of the company, or selling stock be=
cause you are worried that bad governance will lower the long-term value of=
 the company =E2=80=94=C2=A0are totally normal things for responsible inves=
tment managers to do.
Unless they run money for New Hampshire, in which case this might become a =
felony? Believe me, if it does, Elon Musk will hear about it.

Investor: Elon, thanks for meeting with us. I=E2=80=99m worried that you ke=
ep demanding tens of billions of dollars of stock awards, selling the stock=
 to buy distracting toys, and then extracting more stock by threatening to =
spend more time with the toys. Could you just try to focus a bit more on do=
ing your job as CEO of Tesla?
Musk: I=E2=80=99m calling the police! You considered governance! You=E2=80=
=99re going to prison for 20 years!

I=E2=80=99m sorry, this is so stupid. =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D is essentially=
=C2=A0about considering certain risks to a company=E2=80=99s financial resu=
lts: You might want to avoid investing in a company if its factories are go=
ing to be washed away by rising oceans, or if its main product is going to =
be regulated out of existence, or if its  position on controversial social =
issues will cost it sales, or if its CEO controls the board and spends too =
much corporate money on wasteful personal projects. Obviously ESG in practi=
ce is also other, more controversial things:
=09If you care about the environment, social issues, etc., you might want t=
o invest in companies that you think are environmentally or socially good, =
whether or not they are good financial investments.=09You might incorrectly=
 convince yourself that the stuff you think is environmentally or socially =
good is also good for the bottom line: You might have a wishful estimate of=
 how quickly the world will transition away from fossil fuels, to justify y=
our desire not to invest in oil companies. You might tell yourself =E2=80=
=9Cthis company=E2=80=99s stance on social issues will cost it lots of cust=
omers=E2=80=9D when really the customers don=E2=80=99t care, but you do.

But if you make it a crime for investors to consider certain financial risk=
s=C2=A0then you get too much of those risks.
In particular, I suspect, you get too much governance risk. If every invest=
or tomorrow said =E2=80=9Cokay we don=E2=80=99t care about the environment,=
=E2=80=9D most companies probably wouldn=E2=80=99t ramp up their pollution:=
 Their executives probably don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0want=C2=A0to pollute unnecess=
arily, polluting probably wouldn=E2=80=99t help the bottom line, and many c=
ompanies just sit at computers developing software and couldn=E2=80=99t pol=
lute much if they wanted to. But if every investor tomorrow said =E2=80=9Co=
kay we don=E2=80=99t care about governance,=E2=80=9D then, I mean, =E2=80=
=9Cgovernance=E2=80=9D is just a way of saying =E2=80=9Csomebody makes sure=
 that the CEO is doing a good job and doesn=E2=80=99t pay herself too much.=
=E2=80=9D If the investors don=E2=80=99t care about that, then a lot of CEO=
s will be happy to give themselves raises and spend more time  on the corpo=
