I=E2=80=99ve   said this before, but one of the great weird business opport=
unities in the US financial industry is that nondisclosure agreements are i=
llegal, and you can get paid for reporting=C2=A0them to the US Securities a=
nd Exchange Commission. This is very counterintuitive, which I suppose make=
s it lucrative: If you find a nondisclosure agreement and send it to the SE=
C, maybe you=E2=80=99ll be the first to report it, so you can get paid. Thi=
s is neither legal nor business advice but it sure is weird.
Here=E2=80=99s how it works. The SEC has a rule,  Rule 240.21F-17, which is=
 often called a =E2=80=9Cwhistleblower protection=E2=80=9D rule. The idea i=
s that, if you work at a financial services firm and you witness securities=
 fraud, the SEC wants you to come to them and report it. And Rule 240.21F-1=
7 says that your employer can=E2=80=99t retaliate against you for reporting=
 fraud to the SEC. Specifically, it says:
No person may take any=C2=A0action=C2=A0to impede an individual from commun=
icating directly with the Commission staff about a possible securities law =
violation, including enforcing, or threatening to enforce, a confidentialit=
y agreement =E2=80=A6=C2=A0with respect to such communications.
And so if you show up for your first day of work at a financial firm, and t=
hey make you sign a nondisclosure agreement saying =E2=80=9CI will not disc=
lose the company=E2=80=99s secret information,=E2=80=9D which is pretty sta=
ndard, and then you discover fraud and report it to the SEC, your company i=
s not allowed to say =E2=80=9Cwell you signed this NDA and you reported our=
 secrets (fraud) to the SEC, so you breached your contract, so we=E2=80=99r=
e going to sue.=E2=80=9D They=E2=80=99re not allowed to fire you for it, th=
ey=E2=80=99re not allowed to sue to enforce the NDA, and they=E2=80=99re no=
t even allowed to=C2=A0threaten=C2=A0to sue to enforce the NDA.
But the SEC actually interprets this rule more broadly: They=E2=80=99re not=
 allowed to even=C2=A0have=C2=A0the NDA. After all, if you sign an NDA sayi=
ng =E2=80=9CI will not disclose the company=E2=80=99s secret information,=
=E2=80=9D that might deter you from reporting fraud to the SEC. You might t=
hink=C2=A0to yourself =E2=80=9Cuh oh, I signed an NDA, I can=E2=80=99t tell=
 the SEC about this fraud, it=E2=80=99s secret, and I=E2=80=99m not allowed=
 to disclose the company=E2=80=99s secrets.=E2=80=9D So you won=E2=80=99t r=
eport the fraud. Nobody has=C2=A0explicitly threatened=C2=A0to sue you, but=
 the NDA=C2=A0itself=C2=A0serves as that threat: You signed a legal documen=
t promising not to disclose stuff, which might scare you into not disclosin=
g it to the SEC.
If the NDA explicitly says =E2=80=9CI will not disclose the company=E2=80=
=99s secret information, except, to be clear, I am allowed to say anything =
I want to the SEC or any other regulator,=E2=80=9D then that=E2=80=99s fine=
. (Not legal advice!) But if the NDA=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0say that =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0even if it says something pretty close to that=C2=A0=E2=80=94=
=C2=A0then=C2=A0the SEC might take the view that it is an illegal threat to=
 deter whistleblowing.
So yesterday JPMorgan Chase & Co.=E2=80=99s J.P. Morgan Securities division=
=C2=A0 agreed to pay $18 million for writing its=C2=A0client=C2=A0NDAs wron=
g:

According to the SEC=E2=80=99s order, from March 2020 through July 2023, JP=
MS regularly asked retail clients to sign confidential release agreements i=
f they had been issued a credit or settlement from the firm of more than $1=
,000. The agreements required the clients to keep confidential the settleme=
nt, all underlying facts relating to the settlement, and all information re=
lating to the account at issue. In addition, even though the agreements per=
mitted clients to respond to SEC inquiries, they did not permit clients to =
voluntarily contact the SEC.
=E2=80=9CWhether it=E2=80=99s in your employment contracts, settlement agre=
ements or elsewhere, you simply cannot include provisions that prevent indi=
viduals from contacting the SEC with evidence of wrongdoing,=E2=80=9D said =
Gurbir S. Grewal, Director of the SEC=E2=80=99s Division of Enforcement.

The  SEC says:

The Release used by JPMS from March 2020 through July 2023 contained langua=
ge providing a release of liability and a provision that stated, =E2=80=9Ct=
he [JPMS client] promises not to sue or solicit others to institute any act=
ion or proceeding against [JPMS] arising out of events concerning the Accou=
nt=E2=80=9D and that if the JPMS client breaches that provision, JPMS =E2=
=80=9Cmay undertake whatever legal action they deem appropriate to address =
the breach(s), including, but not limited to, injunctive relief, and moneta=
ry damages not to exceed the settlement amount.=E2=80=9D
In a separate paragraph, the Release stated: =E2=80=9C[the JPMS client] sha=
ll keep this Agreement confidential and not use or disclose (including but =
not limited to, media statements, social media, or otherwise) the allegatio=
ns, facts, contentions, liability, damages, or other information relating i=
n any way to the Account, including but not limited to, the existence or te=
rms of this Agreement . . . . Notwithstanding, [JPMS client] and [JPMS clie=
nt=E2=80=99s] attorneys are neither prohibited nor restricted from respondi=
ng to any inquiry about this settlement or its underlying facts by FINRA, t=
he SEC, or any other government entity or self-regulatory organization, or =
as required by law.=E2=80=9D

The clients were explicitly allowed to answer=C2=A0questions=C2=A0from the =
SEC, but not to go to the SEC themselves. JPMorgan =E2=80=9Cforced certain =
clients into the untenable position of choosing between receiving settlemen=
ts or credits from the firm and reporting potential securities law violatio=
ns to the SEC,=E2=80=9D says Grewal, but I am not sure that=E2=80=99s right=
. If you signed this release then (1) you got the money from JPMorgan, (2) =
you could=C2=A0definitely=C2=A0still go to the SEC to report the violation,=
 (3) JPMorgan couldn=E2=80=99t do anything=C2=A0about it (because of Rule=
=C2=A0240.21F-17), and (4) now you could=C2=A0also=C2=A0go to the SEC, tell=
 them =E2=80=9Chey check out this nondisclosure clause,=E2=80=9D and the SE=
C would sue and you could collect a whistleblower payment. The release was =
just an extra windfall for the clients, if they were sharp enough to notice=
 it.

