<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">NDAs</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=E2=80=99ve <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/34031994.258404/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTAtMDMvdGhlLXNlYy1oYWQtYS1idXN5LXdlZWs_Y21waW=
Q9QkJEMDExNzI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZ=
XR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMTE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB9a51a47f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">  said this before</a>, but one of the great =
weird business opportunities in the US financial industry is that nondisclo=
sure agreements are illegal, and you can get paid for reporting=C2=A0them t=
o the US Securities and Exchange Commission. This is very counterintuitive,=
 which I suppose makes it lucrative: If you find a nondisclosure agreement =
and send it to the SEC, maybe you=E2=80=99ll be the first to report it, so =
you can get paid. This is neither legal nor business advice but it sure is =
weird.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s how it works. The SEC has a rul=
e, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34031994.258404=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGF3LmNvcm5lbGwuZWR1L2Nmci90ZXh0LzE3LzI0MC4yMUYtMTc/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB1a6880ad" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Rule 240.21F-17</a>, which is often c=
alled a =E2=80=9Cwhistleblower protection=E2=80=9D rule. The idea is that, =
if you work at a financial services firm and you witness securities fraud, =
the SEC wants you to come to them and report it. And Rule 240.21F-17 says t=
hat your employer can=E2=80=99t retaliate against you for reporting fraud t=
o the SEC. Specifically, it says:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No person may take any=C2=A0action=
=C2=A0to impede an individual from communicating directly with the Commissi=
on staff about a possible securities law violation, including enforcing, or=
 threatening to enforce, a confidentiality agreement =E2=80=A6=C2=A0with re=
spect to such communications.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so if you show up for your first day of wo=
rk at a financial firm, and they make you sign a nondisclosure agreement sa=
ying =E2=80=9CI will not disclose the company=E2=80=99s secret information,=
=E2=80=9D which is pretty standard, and then you discover fraud and report =
it to the SEC, your company is not allowed to say =E2=80=9Cwell you signed =
this NDA and you reported our secrets (fraud) to the SEC, so you breached y=
our contract, so we=E2=80=99re going to sue.=E2=80=9D They=E2=80=99re not a=
llowed to fire you for it, they=E2=80=99re not allowed to sue to enforce th=
e NDA, and they=E2=80=99re not even allowed to=C2=A0<em>threaten=C2=A0</em>=
to sue to enforce the NDA.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the SEC actually interprets this rule more=
 broadly: They=E2=80=99re not allowed to even=C2=A0<em>have=C2=A0</em>the N=
DA. After all, if you sign an NDA saying =E2=80=9CI will not disclose the c=
ompany=E2=80=99s secret information,=E2=80=9D that might deter you from rep=
orting fraud to the SEC. You might think=C2=A0<em>to yourself </em>=E2=80=
=9Cuh oh, I signed an NDA, I can=E2=80=99t tell the SEC about this fraud, i=
t=E2=80=99s secret, and I=E2=80=99m not allowed to disclose the company=E2=
=80=99s secrets.=E2=80=9D So you won=E2=80=99t report the fraud. Nobody has=
=C2=A0<em>explicitly threatened=C2=A0</em>to sue you, but the NDA=C2=A0<em>=
itself=C2=A0</em>serves as that threat: You signed a legal document promisi=
ng not to disclose stuff, which might scare you into not disclosing it to t=
he SEC.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If the NDA explicitly says =E2=80=9CI will not=
 disclose the company=E2=80=99s secret information, except, to be clear, I =
am allowed to say anything I want to the SEC or any other regulator,=E2=80=
=9D then that=E2=80=99s fine. (Not legal advice!) But if the NDA=C2=A0<em>d=
oesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>say that =E2=80=94=C2=A0even if it says something =
pretty close to that=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0then=C2=A0the SEC might take the v=
iew that it is an illegal threat to deter whistleblowing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So yesterday JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co.=E2=80=99=
s J.P. Morgan Securities division=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/34031994.258404/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZX=
NzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyNC03/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB30da9ebc" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> agreed t=
o pay $18 million</a> for writing its=C2=A0<em>client=C2=A0</em>NDAs wrong:=
</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to the SEC=E2=80=99s order, from Mar=
ch 2020 through July 2023, JPMS regularly asked retail clients to sign conf=
idential release agreements if they had been issued a credit or settlement =
from the firm of more than $1,000. The agreements required the clients to k=
eep confidential the settlement, all underlying facts relating to the settl=
ement, and all information relating to the account at issue. In addition, e=
ven though the agreements permitted clients to respond to SEC inquiries, th=
ey did not permit clients to voluntarily contact the SEC.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWhether it=E2=80=99s in your employme=
nt contracts, settlement agreements or elsewhere, you simply cannot include=
 provisions that prevent individuals from contacting the SEC with evidence =
of wrongdoing,=E2=80=9D said Gurbir S. Grewal, Director of the SEC=E2=80=99=
s Division of Enforcement.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/34031994.258404/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9maWxlcy9saXRpZ2F0=
aW9uL2FkbWluLzIwMjQvMzQtOTkzNDQucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa72bc3ff" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> SEC says</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Release used by JPMS from March 2020 throu=
gh July 2023 contained language providing a release of liability and a prov=
ision that stated, =E2=80=9Cthe [JPMS client] promises not to sue or solici=
t others to institute any action or proceeding against [JPMS] arising out o=
f events concerning the Account=E2=80=9D and that if the JPMS client breach=
es that provision, JPMS =E2=80=9Cmay undertake whatever legal action they d=
eem appropriate to address the breach(s), including, but not limited to, in=
junctive relief, and monetary damages not to exceed the settlement amount.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a separate paragraph, the Release stated: =
=E2=80=9C[the JPMS client] shall keep this Agreement confidential and not u=
se or disclose (including but not limited to, media statements, social medi=
a, or otherwise) the allegations, facts, contentions, liability, damages, o=
r other information relating in any way to the Account, including but not l=
imited to, the existence or terms of this Agreement . . . . Notwithstanding=
, [JPMS client] and [JPMS client=E2=80=99s] attorneys are neither prohibite=
d nor restricted from responding to any inquiry about this settlement or it=
s underlying facts by FINRA, the SEC, or any other government entity or sel=
f-regulatory organization, or as required by law.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The clients were explicitly allowed to answer=
=C2=A0<em>questions=C2=A0</em>from the SEC, but not to go to the SEC themse=
lves. JPMorgan =E2=80=9Cforced certain clients into the untenable position =
of choosing between receiving settlements or credits from the firm and repo=
rting potential securities law violations to the SEC,=E2=80=9D says Grewal,=
 but I am not sure that=E2=80=99s right. If you signed this release then (1=
) you got the money from JPMorgan, (2) you could=C2=A0<em>definitely=C2=A0<=
/em>still go to the SEC to report the violation, (3) JPMorgan couldn=E2=80=
=99t do anything=C2=A0about it (because of Rule=C2=A0240.21F-17), and (4) n=
ow you could=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>go to the SEC, tell them =E2=80=9Chey =
check out this nondisclosure clause,=E2=80=9D and the SEC would sue and you=
 could collect a whistleblower payment. The release was just an extra windf=
all for the clients, if they were sharp enough to notice it.</p>
