<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A simple story that you could tell is that the=
 banking system is in the business of borrowing short to lend long. There i=
s a lot of natural demand for long-term loans (government deficits need fin=
ancing, people need mortgages) and a lot of natural demand for places to pa=
rk money that can be withdrawn at any time (people need checking accounts),=
 but a mismatch between them. More people want to borrow long than lend lon=
g; more people want to lend short than borrow short.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so traditionally banks intermediate that; =
they borrow short to lend long. And that is a well-known risky business mod=
el, and there are various ways to mitigate that risk, and the most importan=
t is the lender of last resort: If banks have lots of long-term good loans =
funded with short-term deposits, and all the depositors ask for their money=
 back, the central bank will lend cash to the banks to pay back their depos=
itors.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this risk is particularly acute when inter=
est rates have been very low for a long time, and then rapidly rise to a mu=
ch higher level. All the banks have long-term loans that they made at the l=
ow interest rates,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backg=
round-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but now they have to pay high interest rates on deposits. One thi=
ng that this means is that their operating profits are lower or negative: I=
f your assets are a bunch of mortgages paying 3%, and your liabilities are =
a bunch of savings deposits paying 2%, you=E2=80=99re losing 1% every year.=
 The other thing that this means is that they are=C2=A0<em>mark-to-market i=
nsolvent:=C2=A0</em>If your assets are a bunch of mortgages paying 3%, and =
now mortgage rates are 6%, your mortgages are worth like 80 cents on the do=
llar, and if you=E2=80=99re a bank with 10% equity and your assets have los=
t 20% of their value, you are insolvent.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so when the Fed raises rates a lot very qu=
ickly, that has the possible effect of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0bankrupting all the b=
anks? Or getting them kind of close to insolvency, anyway? And in fact last=
 year there was a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
34031994.258404/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzI=
wMjMtMDMtMTAvc3RhcnR1cC1iYW5rLWhhZC1hLXN0YXJ0dXAtYmFuay1ydW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMD=
ExNzI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImd=
XRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMTE3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cBa541e1ad" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> bit of a crisis</a> among <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34031994.258404/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLm=
NvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDYtMTQvcmVnaW9uYWwtYmFua3MtZG9uLXQtZmVlb=
C1sb3ZlZD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTE3MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9z=
b3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAxMTcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB701c0f47" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> US regional banks</a>, which r=
eally were in this business of borrowing short to lend long and turned out =
to be, in some cases, insolvent when the Fed raised rates rapidly.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are ways to mitigate this risk, too. One=
 is: You have regulation to make the banks more robust to this. You have ca=
pital regulation (they can=E2=80=99t have too little capital), and also liq=
uidity regulations that have=C2=A0the effect of lowering the duration of th=
eir assets and increasing the duration of their liabilities, and prudential=
 oversight where the bank regulators call up the banks and say =E2=80=9Crea=
lly? You=E2=80=99re funding all these 30-year=C2=A0mortgages with overnight=
 deposits?=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A more important way is accounting: Banks=C2=
=A0<em>do not have to recognize interest-rate losses=C2=A0</em>on huge swat=
hes of their assets, loans and bonds that they classify as =E2=80=9Cheld to=
 maturity.=E2=80=9D This is the essential trick that makes all of banking w=
ork: When interest rates go up, the market value of banks=E2=80=99 long-ter=
m loans goes down, but the banks=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t have to realize tho=
se losses</em>; they just hold the loans until maturity and get paid back 1=
00 cents on the dollar.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The US regional banking crisis last year turne=
d on the fact that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/34031994.258404/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLz=
IwMjMtMDUtMDQvbm9ib2R5LXRydXN0cy10aGUtYmFua3Mtbm93P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMTcyNF9NT=
05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJt=
PTI0MDExNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0e55cce=
8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> this doesn=E2=80=99t work as well as it used to</a>: The bank=
s do not recognize the losses in their main accounting statements, but they=
 do=C2=A0<em>disclose=C2=A0</em>the losses, and people=C2=A0can read that d=
isclosure and panic. And when they panic, they take out their deposits. And=
 then the banks need to raise money. They can=E2=80=99t do this by selling =
their loans, because then they=E2=80=99d recognize their losses and become =
insolvent. And they can=E2=80=99t do it by borrowing from the Fed, because=
=C2=A0<em>the Fed lends against the market value of the loans</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One solution is for the Fed to instead lend ba=
nks money against the=C2=A0<em>par=C2=A0</em>value of their loans, their ho=
ld-to-maturity value. And <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/34031994.258404/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTMvc3ZiLWNvdWxkbi10LWlnbm9yZS1pdHMtbG9zc2VzLWJ1dC10aGUtZm=
VkLWNhbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTE3MjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb=
3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAxMTcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4d302d28" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> that=E2=80=99s what it did</a>:=
 It created the Bank Term Funding Program, which allows banks to post colla=
teral (Treasury bonds, agency mortgage-backed securities) with the Fed and =
borrow=C2=A0<em>the par value=C2=A0</em>of those assets. If a bank has $100=
 of mortgage bonds that are worth $80 because rates went up, it can borrow =
$100, solving the liquidity problem.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is another way to look at this. Forg=
et individual banks and think of the banking system as a whole. The system =
holds long-term assets (loans, mortgages, Treasury bonds) and has short-ter=
m liabilities (deposits). It therefore has a lot of interest-rate risk, bot=
h to its income and to its balance sheet:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If rates go up, the banking system ha=
s to pay more interest on its deposits, but doesn=E2=80=99t get any more in=
terest on its loans (mortgages, Treasuries, etc.), so it makes less profit.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If rates go up, the banking syste=
m=E2=80=99s long-term assets lose value, so it has big mark-to-market losse=
s.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is sort of loosely true as an abstract ma=
tter. It is quite true of a lot of banks, particularly a lot of US regional=
 banks. It is not particularly true of a lot of the big US banks, and in fa=
ct rising rates have generally been=C2=A0<em>good=C2=A0</em>for them,=C2=A0=
for a combination of real and accounting reasons.<a class=3D"footnote-index=
" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display=
: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You know whom it is weirdly true of? The Feder=
al Reserve. The Wall Street Journal <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/34031994.258404/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9lY29ub215L2Nlb=
nRyYWwtYmFua2luZy9mZWQtcG9zdHMtbGFyZ2VzdC1ldmVyLWFubnVhbC1vcGVyYXRpbmctbG9z=
cy02ZTI0OWEzOT9tb2Q9aHBfbWFqb3JfcG9zMSNjeHJlY3Nfcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B8c756207" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> reported on Friday</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Federal Reserve ran an operating loss of $=
114.3 billion last year, its largest ever, a consequence of its campaign to=
 aggressively support the economy in 2020 and 2021, then jacking up interes=
t rates to combat high inflation. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The central bank paid more to financial instit=
utions on interest-bearing deposits and securities than it earned from secu=
rities that it bought when interest rates were lower. That=E2=80=99s a resu=
lt of it raising its benchmark short-term interest rate to a two-decade hig=
h, above 5%, last year=E2=80=A6.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fed losses are a side effect of its efforts to=
 support the economy during the Covid-19 pandemic by purchasing large amoun=
ts of Treasury and mortgage-backed securities. The market value of those se=
curities dropped after the central bank began raising rates aggressively in=
 2022 to combat inflation, but the Fed doesn=E2=80=99t book losses on them =
because they are held to maturity.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead, the Fed is running losses because it =
is paying more in interest than it earns on those securities. Beginning in =
September 2022, the overnight rates the Fed pays to banks on their deposits=
 held at the Fed, called reserves, and on other securities transactions it =
conducts to manage interest rates, exceeded the income it collects on its $=
7.1 trillion in security holdings.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Fed, in recent years, borrows short to len=
d long, in enormous size, without the sort of caution that regular banks us=
e.=C2=A0<em>Abstractly</em>, banks borrow with overnight deposits and inves=
t in long-term mortgages, but=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em>they do a lot of lo=
ng-term borrowing and own a lot of short-term assets to hedge their liquidi=
ty and interest-rate risk. The Fed has a much, much better way to hedge liq=
uidity risk =E2=80=94=C2=A0it can just print dollars =E2=80=94=C2=A0so does=
n=E2=80=99t worry about that. It just does, literally and in large size, th=
e thing that banks sometimes sort of abstractly do. And it doesn=E2=80=99t =
worry about the interest-rate risk because:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It accounts for its assets on a held-=
to-maturity basis, so it doesn=E2=80=99t book losses when rates go up.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It really can hold those assets to mat=
urity, because if anyone wants dollars it can just print dollars, so it tru=
ly never needs to sell assets.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And even the operating loss doesn=E2=80=99t re=
ally matter. The Journal goes on:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The losses don=E2=80=99t affect the Fed=E2=80=
=99s day-to-day operations and won=E2=80=99t require the central bank to as=
k for an infusion from the Treasury Department. Unlike federal agencies, th=
e Fed doesn=E2=80=99t have to go to Congress hat in hand to cover operating=
 losses. Instead, the Fed created an IOU in 2022 that it calls a =E2=80=9Cd=
eferred asset.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Fed=E2=80=99s deferred asset grew by $116.=
4 billion last year, bringing its cumulative total to $133 billion. When th=
e Fed is no longer running losses, it will pay itself back first and exting=
uish the deferred asset before resuming remittances to the Treasury.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CDeferred asset=E2=80=9D is a great te=
rm. The Fed is not a regular bank. If it has losses, that just means that i=
t owes itself money, and it will eventually pay itself back. And it can hol=
d that debt to maturity.</p>
